</div>'''Level 866''', also known as "Giza's Fate" or "The Pyramids", is the 867th level of [[Backrooms Wiki|the Backrooms]]. It was discovered on between the 1600s-1800s.
==<div class="egypt">'''Overview''' "𓅱𓆯𓅂𓂋𓆯𓇋𓅂𓅃"</div>==
{{Blurimage|file=Level 866 Giza's Fate.png|caption=The most popular photograph of '''Level 866'''.|width=250px}}
'''Level 866''' resembles the interior of the ancient pyramids of Giza in [[the Frontrooms]] with an infinite number of ancient corridors and rooms. Several torches and other artificial lights are scattered sparsely across the level, serving as the only illumination source. '''Level 866''' is filled with a wide range of traps, with density varying for each area. The walls are adorned with paintings and small holes that lead into enormous bodies of sand that surround the entire level. There are also several environmental hazards like fires, earthquakes, blackouts, and caved ceilings. '''Level 866''' is very hot, with its hottest recorded temperatures surpass 100 degrees Celsius, however, such temperatures are quite rare.

'''Level 866''' runs low on many Backrooms resources, with [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]] and [[Object 5|Greek Fire]] being the most common, though they are still found in very small quantities. Other non-Backrooms resources, like water and nourishment, can commonly be found on corners and in hallways. Drinks and food here suffer a strange effect that causes them to look rotten, or miscolored, although it is still proper for consumption. Sand sometimes , which is often a warning of an encounter with '''The Pharaoh'''. Puzzles are often found when searching deeper areas; solving them will reveal minor rewards and small pieces of metal and gold.{{Blurimage|file=Level 866 Giza's Fate 3.png|caption=A room on '''Level 866'''.|width=250px}}Hieroglyphic codes and phrases can be found all around '''Level 866'''. Solving them without a team of historians has been deemed impossible; however, if one can solve them, it is rumored they might unveil the secrets of this level: answers to the trials and puzzles, maps for secret areas, and other ammenities. Although, most of the solved codes have led to dead ends. The solved codes in question seem to be memorials to pharaohs, tax and other governmental documents, math equations, representations of gods, literature, etc.

There are a few small hidden rooms spread around '''Level 866'''; these rooms are much less guarded than '''The Tomb'''; they are guarded behind only one enigma, which, when solved, reveals several bottles of [[Object 1|Almond Water]] and [[Achrophiline]], along with aid, canned food, and jewelry. Strangely, these rooms often collapse and are buried by sand, possibly due to the old doors opening or nearby explorers' movements. It is a reason for historians and researchers to discourage the heists of the rooms to preserve '''Level 866''''s layout and historical importance.

{{Blurimage|file=Level 866 Hallway.jpg|caption=A long hallway.|align=right}}

'''Level 866''' is continuously decaying as areas are buried by sand, and important historical artifacts are being burned or damaged by water. The integrity of the underground structure is becoming weak and loose, possibly due to the infinitely large pile of sand just above the level. '''The Tomb''' and its sections have only partially burned down. The resources are running out. The temperatures are rising, and artificial illumination is malfunctioning. The hieroglyphs have been deformed and erased beyond repair, as the sandstone becomes loose. It is predicted that the level will be completely destroyed in the following decades.

===<div class="egypt">'''Three Pyramids Theory ''' "𓏏𓉔𓂋𓅂𓅂 𓊪𓇌𓂋𓄿𓅓𓇋𓂧𓋴 𓏏𓉔𓅂𓅱𓂋𓇌"</div>===
{{Blurimage|align=right|file=Pyramid Scheme.png|caption=An early representation of the theory.|width=280px}}
The Three Pyramids Theory suggests that '''Level 866''' does contain pyramids beyond the interior. The theory suggests the main area of the level is an underground "burrow," or "graveyard," that extends infinitely west and east, and is connected to three pyramids by a triangular channel structure. The three pyramids, occasionally referred to as West, East, and Minor, are made of a hard sandstone that is near impossible to break. Supposedly, outside the pyramids would be filled with unknown entities and contain very extreme conditions, like droughts and impossibly high temperatures. 

Another theory, named "Stolen Body Theory," suggests the Minor Pyramid would have previously been the largest pyramid of the three until, suddenly, a large portion of it disappeared, leaving only the top of the pyramid. The base may have disappeared due to continuous decay, possibly sinking into the sand, being annexed into other pyramids, or no-clipping outside the level.

==<div class="egypt">'''The Tomb''' "𓏏𓉔𓅂 𓏏𓅱𓅓𓃀"</div>==
On '''March 20, 2019''', a crew of field researchers assigned to the exploration of '''Level 866''' by the [[Backroom Colonists|Backrooms Colonists]] unearthed mysterious sand-brick passageways secluded beneath the sandy terrain. Deep and perilous expeditions into the pyramids led to the discovery of what is now known as '''The Tomb'''. Talk of treasures like jewels, gold, and artifacts hidden behind hazards and puzzles has caused greedy and clueless bandits to seek out '''Level 866''' in pursuit of wealth and a rumored, yet disproven, exit from [[Backrooms Wiki|the Backrooms]], all sequestered within '''The Tomb'''.{{Blurimage|file=Level 866 Giza's Fate 4.jpg|caption=A section of '''The Tomb'''.|width=250px}}Infiltrating '''The Tomb''' can be achieved by inscribing certain Egyptian hieroglyphs into abnormal streaks of sand. '''Level 866''' will reveal the correct combination of symbols given ample exploration of the level: Hieroglyphic writing may glimmer on the sides of turned-over bricks and stony artifacts, although the required order is always changing, and an attempt at documenting the answer would become outdated within days. Nonetheless, '''The Tomb''' can also be reportedly accessed by performing an uncanny ritual in the presence of the '''Pharaoh'''. But due to the elevated trap count resulting from how far wanderers have to venture to witness the '''Pharaoh''', in addition to the immense danger already posed by the '''Pharaoh''', this method is inadvisable.

===<div class="egypt">'''The Entrance''' "𓏏𓉔𓅂 𓅂𓈖𓏏𓂋𓄿𓈖𓎢𓅂"</div> ===
'''The Entrance''' is the first known region of '''The Tomb'''. The heist begins on an unstable, wooden bridge. The few and far between wooden planks must be meticulously crossed to avoid dropping into the dark and gaping ravine beneath it. The pristine walls are adorned with shimmering gold and sapphire murals. This handiwork alters regularly to depict recent, harrowing failures of raid attempts, which act as a final warning to turn back before there is no hope of doing so.

===<div class="egypt">'''The Chambers''' "𓏏𓉔𓅂 𓎢𓉔𓄿𓅓𓃀𓅂𓂋𓋴"</div>===

The sandy, ruined entrance to the next area of '''The Tomb''', '''The Chambers''', awaits those brave enough to cross the bridge. '''The Chambers''' are a maze of stone chambers, adorned with a number of items reflecting the ancient Egyptian civilization. There is no artificial lighting on '''the Chambers''', only fires and torches; due to this, fires are quite common on '''the Chambers'''. The heist follows into the intricate maze of stone chambers while simultaneously avoiding the many fires; no matter how much one tries, the fires cannot be put down, and water only grows them. Upon encountering the exit of '''the Chambers''', one will be faced with '''the Trials'''. 

===<div class="egypt">'''The Trials''' "𓏏𓉔𓅂 𓏏𓂋𓇋𓄿𓃭𓋴"</div>===
'''The Trials''' are the second known region of '''The Tomb'''; they are a number of segmented rooms, each with an enigma, puzzle, or difficult challenge, becoming more and more difficult as the rooms pass. All of the enigmas are written in riddles and codes written in hieroglyphs, contributing to the difficulty. The enigmas range from chess, solving physics problems, and extremely difficult, unsolved enigmas and riddles that only highly intelligent people could solve. The challenges require a wanderer to hold extreme physical force and speed to vanquish them; they range from simple activities to difficult maze-like, parkour challenges that are considered perilous.

Upon finalizing all of the challenges, all of the wanderers on the group will see the door opening and gain access to the final area of '''The Tomb''': '''the''' '''Too-Far-Gone'''.

===<div class="egypt">'''The Too-Far-Gone''' "𓏏𓉔𓅂 𓏏𓅱𓆑𓄿𓂋𓎼𓅱𓈖𓅂"</div>===<!--there is no prize ther eis no treasurejdgkjjkdfg greed-->
'''The Too-Far-Gone''' is the final region of '''The Tomb''', and not much is known regarding it, as very few have reached them and even fewer have left them. '''The Too-Far-Gone''' is an massive gallery of pits, holes, and drops, shrouded in the darkness, with no natural or artificial illumination sources. The walls are adorned with stones and hieroglyphs, according to few, they read strange passages about lies and tricks, '''The Too-Far-Gone''' is often considered a point of no return as the doors quickly close after entrance, and opening them is near impossible after closure due to their weight.

Some researchers have concluded that there was never a prize, treasure, or reward on '''The Tomb'''. This theory stands mainly on the fact that no trace of treasure was ever found. Researchers have tried spreading the word, but communication in '''Level 866''' is difficult, and some refuse to believe it. Other researchers counter this theory, arguing that the lack of any light and sound makes it near impossible for one to see the treasure and that it may also be hidden away as a final challenge to the explorers.

==<div class="egypt">'''The Pharaoh''' "𓏏𓉔𓅂 𓊪𓉔𓄿𓂋𓄿𓅱𓉔"</div>==
'''The Pharaoh''' is a recurring theme on the walls and gates whose décor remains intact. Stories of a ghostly, blue and yellow figure emerging during great expeditions between thirty and fifty kilometers into '''Level 866'''<nowiki/>'s pyramids supposedly surfaced after the level's discovery. Bruised survivors of the fallen groups that beheld this entity describe a volatile creature that showed no mercy during its frenzies, of which there were no obvious prior indications. Victims of '''The Pharaoh''' wind up mottled and broken beyond repair, insinuating that '''The Pharaoh''' employs excruciating methods of attack.

As previously mentioned, '''The Pharaoh''' manifests as a result of extensive exploration into the pyramids of '''Level 866'''. Even so, this alone is typically not enough for '''The Pharaoh''' to make an appearance—unfavorable conditions faced by travelers, such as dehydration, exhaustion, and gloomy morale, have been reported to significantly increase the chance of an encounter. Therefore, it is ill-advised to underestimate the amount of food, water, and equipment needed. To combat the psychological aspect, forms of meditation should be practiced among group members to relieve the potential anxiety that might lead to an encounter.

===<div class="egypt">'''Pharaoh Encounter Signs''' "𓊪𓉔𓄿𓂋𓄿𓅱𓉔 𓅂𓈖𓎢𓅱𓅲𓈖𓏏𓅂𓂋 𓋴𓇋𓎼𓈖𓋴"</div>===
